<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Denktas Notes `Shortcomings' in Clinton Report </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Denktas Notes `Shortcomings' in Clinton Report </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1904113394 Nicosia Bayrak Radio in Turkish 1030 GMT 19 Apr 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1904113394 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Bayrak Radio </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Rauf Denktas has said that if the United 
States had treated the sides in the Cyprus issue equally, the 
problem would have been solved long ago. Denktas made a 
statement after meeting with members of the Turkish Cypriot 
Journalists Union Administrative Council. 
  Commenting on U.S. President Bill Clinton's report to the 
U.S. Congress, Denktas remarked that this report has the same 
shortcomings as the UN secretary general's report. Denktas 
noted that Clinton's report concerns itself more with the 
contacts conducted on the Cyprus problem and underlines the 
importance the United States attaches to this subject, pointing 
out that the report does not mention the provocative armament 
efforts of the Greek Cypriots. 
  The report refers to opportunities but does not outline the 
obstacles before these opportunities, Denktas said, adding that 
the report does not give any messages to the Greek Cypriots to 
the effect that they are on the wrong path. Denktas explained 
that he does not resent that the report refers to Kliridhis as 
president and to himself as honorable, while adding that this 
attitude spoils the Greek Cypriots by granting them the title of 
legitimate government and fails to assist in the solution of the 
Cyprus problem. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

