<H3> <TI>   Ciller Aide Briefs Media on Meeting With Clinton </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ciller Aide Briefs Media on Meeting With Clinton </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1504191294 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1700 
GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1504191294 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Zafer Kiraz video report from Washington on 14 April -- </F>
recorded] 
  [Excerpt] [Passage omitted] Ambassador Volkan Vural, 
chief adviser of the Prime Minister's Office, briefed the press 
on Prime Minister Ciller's meeting with President Clinton today. 
According to Vural, during the meeting, Clinton congratulated 
Ciller on the election results. Ciller, in turn, briefed the 
President in detail on the economic stability package. Pointing 
out that the economic program demands sacrifices of everyone in 
Turkey, Ciller noted, however, that the package is vital and the 
coalition government will implement it successfully. The prime 
minister stressed that it will be easier to implement the 
economic stability program with foreign support. 
  Vural reported that during the meeting, Clinton described 
the 
measures adopted in Turkey as an important step. According to 
Vural, Clinton pledged that the United States will extend all 
possible assistance to Turkey in its implementation of the 
program. 
  In accordance with President Suleyman Demirel's request, 
during the meeting, Ciller also briefed Clinton on the recent 
situation in Azerbaijan. Pointing out that she expects 
Washington to undertake an initiative to stop Armenian attacks, 
Ciller also expressed the view that with regard to 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, NATO air operations against the Serbs should 
be conducted whenever necessary. 
  The Cyprus question was also discussed at the meeting. 
Ciller said that Turkey is in favor of reaching an agreement on 
the confidence-building measures [CBM's] package. Ciller added 
that no changes should be made to the CBM's. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

