<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   Agree on Regular Meetings </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Agree on Regular Meetings </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1804152494 Prague CTK in English 1835 GMT 16 Apr 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1804152494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Hamburg, April 16 (CTK) -- It was decided that the 
German and Czech Defense Ministers would meet regularly every 
six months to discuss developments in European and global 
security. 
  Some 144 Czech officers have received or are receiving 
training at military colleges in Germany, said Jaromir Novotny, 
head of the Foreign Relations Section of the Ministry of 
Defense. Joint training courses are under consideration and the 
first joint exercise of staff officers from both armies is 
planned for autumn, he said. 
  Czech soldiers exercised together with Dutch troops in 
March, 
and in July a Czech-French staff officers exercise has been 
scheduled, he said. The aim is for the Czech Army to acquire 
the skills necessary for joint military peacekeeping operations, 
he said. 
  General Karel Pezl, adviser to the Defense Ministry, told 
CTK 
the Czech Army was undergoing a very complex transformation 
process in which the method of leadership was being altered, 
military service shortened from 18 months to one year, and the 
240,000-strong army reduced by a quarter. 

</TEXT>

