<H3> <TI>   Speroni on Speakers' Election, Position Within League </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Speroni on Speakers' Election, Position Within League </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR1804125794 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 2023 GMT 17 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR1804125794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Speroni Sees New Role in League, </F>
Old Habits in Others"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Milan, April 17 -- A leading Northern League 
official, Francesco Speroni, warned here today that, in recent 
political negotiations, he had seen his party's putative 
government allies of Forza Italia and the National Alliance 
using Christian Democrat-style methods he thought were "dead and 
buried." 
  Speroni, who was the League's initial candidate for the 
Senate speakership, said he welcomed the election of the 
conservative Freedom Front's candidate, Carlo Scognamiglio, but 
frowned on how the candidacy had been achieved by the League's 
allies. 
  In particular, he said no one had ever suggested he should 
withdraw his name. He also said the choice fell on Scognamiglio 
largely thanks to the League, since "even" Forza Italia's leader 
Silvio Berlusconi looked kindly on the candidacy of outgoing 
speaker, Giovanni Spadolini, who was backed by the progressives. 
  Speroni told reporters at his home near here that he had 
heard it was President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro who had vetoed his 
candidacy for the Senate. He added that he was standing by his 
refusal to take part in the League's delegation for the 
government-formation negotiations that expected to get under way 
next week. "I'll be sending a deputy," he said. 
  "Maybe, I've come to the end of a political season in the 
League," said Speroni, who is usually ranked as among League 
leader Umberto Bossi's closest aides. "I am not a politician 
for mediation, but one for opposition or an absolute majority. 
I may have to review my role in the League." 

</TEXT>

