<H3> <TI>   Central Bank Cuts Key Interest Rates </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Central Bank Cuts Key Interest Rates </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1604154594 Vienna DIE PRESSE in German 15 Apr 94 p 13 </F>
<F P=103> AU1604154594 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna DIE PRESSE </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Christine Domforth: "Key Rates Decrease, But Not </F>
Lending Interest Rates"] 
  [Excerpts] Vienna -- The Austrian National Bank (OeNB) cut 
the key rates yesterday. The discount rate was decreased from 5 
to 4.75 percent and the Lombard rate from 6 to 5.75 percent. 
The Gomex rate, which is important for the money-procurement 
costs of the banks, was decreased from 5.5 to 5.4 percent. The 
new rates are valid as of today, Friday. The first round of 
interest cuts in 1994 was implemented in mid-February. [passage 
omitted] 
  In an interview with DIE PRESSE, OeNB President Maria 
Schaumayer justified the move using the "harmonization of the 
European interest rate structure" argument. It was also taken 
in anticipation of a decreasing inflation tendency. Austria's 
key rates continue to be lower than the German rates, which, 
according to Schaumayer, is a "sign of strength" and a 
confirmation of Austria's line. She hopes that, as a result of 
the decreased rate of price increases in Germany, Austria will 
again import stability from there in the near future. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

