<H3> <TI>   Kinkel Warns Turkey Over Treatment of Kurds </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kinkel Warns Turkey Over Treatment of Kurds </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1804180294 Berlin DIE WELT in German 18 Apr 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU1804180294 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "State Protection Confirms: PKK </F>
Blackmails Asylum-Seekers"] 
  [Text] Berlin -- FRG Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel has 
warned against consequences for the German-Turkish relations if 
the Turks are indeed using German weapons in their fight against 
Kurds. Kinkel said the reports and documents presented by human 
rights groups will be evaluated. However, it will probably be 
difficult to prove the allegations. 
  Saxony's Interior Minister Heinz Eggert also threatened 
consequences if it turns out that reports about the arrest and 
torture of the Kurdish couple Ramazan and Zubeyde Cetin, who 
were deported to Turkey on 6 April, prove true. Lothar Hermes, 
spokesman of the Saxon Refugee Council, claims that he spoke 
with the Cetins on the telephone on Friday [15 April] and they 
told him about having been mistreated. Eggert expressed "most 
serious doubts" about such reports. If the allegations are 
confirmed, "then the entire discussion about the Kurds in 
Germany must be held in a new way." 
  The Berlin State Protection has confirmed reports by the 
Baden-Wuerttemberg Interior Ministry that the Workers Party of 
Kurdistan (PKK) is blackmailing asylum-seekers. A spokesman 
said the PKK intends to extort 20 million German marks from 
Kurds and Turks in Germany in 1994. 
  In the meantime, 210 ground-to-air missiles for Turkey were 
loaded on the freighter Kayseri near Stadersand on the Lower 
Elbe on Saturday. The loading was originally expected to take 
place in the free port of Hamburg. Protests occurred there, 
however. 

</TEXT>

