<F P=100> GERMANYY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rexrodt Suggests Bonn for WTO Headquarters </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rexrodt Suggests Bonn for WTO Headquarters </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1904170994 Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT in German 18 Apr 94 p 7 </F>
<F P=103> AU1904170994 </F>
<F P=104>  Duesseldorf HANDELSBLATT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["sm"-signed report: "Minister Rexrodt Promotes Bonn as </F>
Seat of Future World Trade Organization"] 
  [Excerpts] Bonn wants to apply for the headquarters of the 
new World Trade Organization (WTO), Economics Minister Guenter 
Rexrodt announced on the sidelines of the signing of the new 
GATT agreement on liberalizing world trade in Marrakesh 
(Morocco). [passage omitted] 
  So far, Geneva has officially applied to house the new WTO. 
However, Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt told journalists 
that he wants to prepare the Federal Government's application 
for Bonn. If there are no reservations by the ministries 
concerned, the cabinet could decide on Bonn's application for 
the WTO headquarters before the summer recess, Rexrodt said. He 
wants to announce the German application in a letter to 
Sutherland in order to document Germany's interest in the WTO 
seat for the preparatory committee. 
  As a former capital, Bonn meets all the requirements, 
Rexrodt 
said, promoting his proposal. It has the necessary 
administrative and conference capacities, and most of the WTO 
countries already have diplomatic missions in Bonn. What also 
speaks in Bonn's favor is that no major international 
organization has its seat in Germany at the moment, which has a 
tradition of advocating free world trade and is one of the 
largest trading nations in the world. 
  The Swiss delegation in Marrakesh was astonished at 
Germany's 
interest in the WTO seat. The Swiss Government is taking Bonn's 
application, competing with Geneva, seriously. Experts say that 
trying to keep the WTO in Geneva might prove expensive for 
Switzerland. A new office building will also be needed in 
Geneva, because the existing GATT headquarters will be too small 
for the WTO. Sutherland wants to discuss conditions with the 
competitors over the next few months. In accordance with its 
share in world trade, Germany is paying some 12 percent toward 
the cost of GATT and the future WTO. The new organization is to 
start work as early as 1 January 1995. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

