<F P=100> GERMANYY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ruehe Rejects Kinkel Criticism of Bundeswehr Strength </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ruehe Rejects Kinkel Criticism of Bundeswehr Strength </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1904160594 Berlin DIE WELT in German 19 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU1904160594 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DIE WELT </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Martin S. Lambeck report: "Ruehe Rejects Kinkel's </F>
Criticism"] 
  [Text] Bonn -- One day before the Constitutional Court 
deals with Bundeswehr missions outside NATO, Defense Minister 
Volker Ruehe (Christian Democratic Union) rejected the criticism 
by Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel (Free Democratic Party of 
Germany) regarding the planned reduction of the Bundeswehr 
yesterday. In an interview with DIE WELT, Ruehe stated that the 
troops will become smaller and be reduced to about 340,000 
because "exercises and investments will again be possible." 
However, he added: "We reserve the right to 370,000 men." 
Kinkel insisted on a strength of 370,000 men. 
  The Chancellor's Office also pointed out that, 
internationally, Germany will reserve the right to 370,000 men. 
Ruehe's conceptional guidelines for the Bundeswehr that will be 
submitted to the defense working group of the Christian 
Democratic Union/Christian Social Union [CDU/CSU] today are 
being supported by Chancellor Helmut Kohl and CDU/CSU Bundestag 
group leader Schaeuble. They stipulate a peacetime strength of 
320,000 to 340,000 men. They also provide for a military 
service of 10 months. 
  Ruehe told DIE WELT: "The weakening of the Bundeswehr is the 
result of expenditure cuts involving 2 billion German marks 
within 12 months. It is now important to strengthen the 
operational readiness of the Bundeswehr by optimizing the use of 
the money." The smaller armed forces will be given structures 
that make it possible to ensure a quick increase to 370,000 men. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

