<H3> <TI>   EU Blames Turkish Side for Lack of Progress </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EU Blames Turkish Side for Lack of Progress </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1904175394 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1600 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1904175394 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Hans Van Den Broek, the European Union [EU] 
Commissioner on Foreign Affairs, and Serge Abou, the EU observer 
at the Cyprus talks, accused the Turkish Cypriot side of making 
it difficult for Abou to carry out his mission properly by 
refusing to meet with him. Van Den Broek and Abou made their 
accusations while briefing the EU Council of Ministers in 
Luxembourg. 
  According to Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation [CyBC] 
correspondent Dhespina Kaloyeropoulou, most ministers agreed 
that the Turkish Cypriot side is causing the most difficulties 
in negotiations for a Cyprus solution. In an interjection, 
Greek Deputy Foreign Minister Yeoryios Papandreou stressed that 
the Cyprus issue has lasted for a long time and is causing 
instability in the region. He suggested that the facts 
presented by the observer at the briefing be put on the record. 
  The Greek deputy foreign minister asked that the procedure 
for beginning negotiations for Cyprus' accession to the EU be 
speeded up. According to CyBC's information, some ministers 
objected vehemently at this point, saying that it is not the 
right time to mention a new expansion when the Council of Europe 
has not yet ratified the upcoming EU expansion by another four 
countries and since the Maastricht Treaty will be reconsidered 
in 1996. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

