<F P=106> [Report signed "M. Na": "Paris Is Willing To Help Train the </F>
Palestinian Police"] 
  [Text] If the Palestinians are to have the 9,000 policemen 
who are to guarantee law and order in Gaza and Jericho when 
Palestinian autonomy comes into force, they must have the 
technical and financial means of doing so, and this is not yet 
the case. 
  So, to speed things up, Yasir 'Abd-Rabbuh, one of Yasir 
'Arafat's advisers, came to Paris on Thursday, 14 April, to have 
talks with the foreign minister. Alain Juppe told him that 
France is willing to contribute to the training, by the national 
gendarmerie, of police officers and junior officers, the bulk of 
whose men are already being trained in Jordan, Egypt, and 
Britain. Paris, according to a Quai d'Orsay [Foreign Ministry] 
spokesman, will also "study" the request for communications 
equipment submitted by the PLO. But the Palestinians also need 
money to pay wages. On Monday, 18 April, Paris will ask its 
European Union partners to use some of the ECU 50 million in 
community aid to the Palestinians for the benefit of the police. 
  After Paris, Mr. 'Abd-al-Rabbuh, who is being accompanied by 
a Norwegian special envoy (Oslo chairs the committee for 
international assistance to the Palestinian police), is due to 
visit Brussels, Bonn, London, Tokyo, Washington, 

</TEXT>

