<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   ICRC, MSF Workers Stage Silent Protest Over Gorazde </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ICRC, MSF Workers Stage Silent Protest Over Gorazde </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2004163994 Paris AFP in English 1632 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2004163994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, April 20 (AFP) -- Red Cross staff and 
doctors working for an international medical charity based in 
besieged Gorazde decided Wednesday [20 April] to remain silent 
for 24 hours to protest against the Serb offensive and their 
inability to help victims of the heavy shelling. 
  Paul-Henri Morard, spokesman for the International Committee 
of the Red Cross [ICRC], said two ICRC staff in the war-torn 
town and two doctors for Medecins Sans Frontieres [MSF--Doctors 
Without Borders] announced the decision in a statement sent to 
Sarajevo. 
  "They announce their intention to remain silent to protest 
against the tragic events in Gorazde and their inability to 
provide help," he said. 
  The ICRC, whose staff avoid taking sides in the many 
conflicts where they offer humanitarian assistance, said it 
sympathised with the protest. 
  "They are profoundly dismayed.... They are unable to collect 
the wounded and assist the victims on all sides," Morard said. 
  The four foreigners, along with four members of the UN High 
Commissioner for Refugees [UNHCR], have until now provided 
information to the outside world about the Bosnian Serb 
offensive against the Moslem enclave in eastern Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

