<DOCNO> FBIS4-19607 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu077aa_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-077 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   North Korea, IAEA Discuss New Inspections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    North Korea, IAEA Discuss New Inspections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2104103094 Paris AFP in English 1010 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2104103094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Vienna, April 21 (AFP) -- Pyongyang officials and 
the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) are discussing 
details of a possible new IAEA inspection of suspected nuclear 
sites in North Korea, a spokesman for the Agency said here 
Thursday [21 April]. 
  David Kyd said the inspection could begin before the end of 
the month as the IAEA wants it to be accomplished as soon as 
possible since the UN Security Council wants a report on the 
matter in May. 
  He added that if Pyongyang agrees to the new inspections, 
the 
IAEA investigators would be ready to leave by next week. 
  Pyongyang refused in March to allow an IAEA team from 
gathering crucial samples at a facility in Yongbyon suspected of 
producing weapons-grade plutonium. 
  The IAEA then voted to ask the UN Security Council to take 
up 
the issue of North Korea's obstinate refusal to allow 
inspections of its nuclear sites but stopped short of calling 
for sanctions against Pyongyang. 
  Kyd said that the current negotiations are not focussing on 
the controversial sites involved in the last visit by the 
inspectors. 

</TEXT>

