<H3> <TI>   VVD, D66 Leaders Vie To Head `Purple' Coalition </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    VVD, D66 Leaders Vie To Head `Purple' Coalition </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2004144994 Rotterdam ALGEMEEN DAGBLAD in Dutch 20 Apr 94 p 
3 </F>

<F P=103> BR2004144994 </F>
<F P=104>  Rotterdam ALGEMEEN DAGBLAD </F>
<F P=105>  Dutch </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Bolkestein Challenges Democrats 66 </F>
To `Build a Bridge'"] 
  [Excerpt] Frits Bolkestein, VVD [People's Party for Freedom 
and Democracy] leader, is not ruling out a "purple" coalition 
between the PvdA [Labor Party], the VVD, and the D66 [Democrats 
66] but does not want to speak out in favor of such a 
possibility at present. He is not ruling out "any serious 
party." Nor does he want to indicate his preference. 
  Yesterday, in a speech at the Erasmus University in 
Rotterdam, he reproached his D66 colleague Van Mierlo for always 
emphatically having flirted with the "purple coalition," 
adopting the viewpoint that if the CDA [Christian Democratic 
Appeal] is stripped of its central power position, then "the 
whole face of the Netherlands will change." 
  In response to the remarks made by Bolkestein, yesterday 
evening in Middelburg, D66 party leader Hans Van Mierlo said 
that he may be prepared to take the lead in forming a "purple" 
coalition including the D66, the VVD, and the PvdA. 
  However, according to Van Mierlo, which party will have to 
adopt a leading role in this respect will depend on the outcome 
of the elections: "Three parties are involved in such a 
`purple' coalition. Furthermore, such an undertaking requires 
great wisdom and unanimity." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

