<F P=100> CANADA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chinese Deputy Premier Seeks Greater Investment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chinese Deputy Premier Seeks Greater Investment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004141794 Montreal Radio Canada International in English 
1330 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2004141794 </F>
<F P=104>  Montreal Radio Canada International </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chinese Vice Premier Zou Jiahua has begun his visit 
to Canada by saying his country can't grow in the next century 
without help. Speaking in Vancouver, Mr. Zou urged a business 
audience to invest more in China, especially in the transport, 
energy, agriculture, communications, and mining sectors. Trade 
between Canada and China is worth more than $4 billion a year. 
  Prime Minister Jean Chretien will visit China in November, 
becoming the first Canadian leader to do so since the 1989 
massacre of pro-democracy activists in Beijing. Mr. Chretien 
has said that human rights questions should not deter closer 
trade links between the two countries. 

</TEXT>

