<H3> <TI>   Questions Usefulness of UN Troops </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Questions Usefulness of UN Troops </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004141694 Lisbon RDP Antena 1 Radio Network in Portuguese 
1100 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2004141694 </F>
<F P=104>  Lisbon RDP Antena 1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] Portuguese Foreign Minister Durao 
Barroso spoke about Bosnia this morning. He said that the 
situation of the blue helmets is becoming unacceptable. 
  [Begin Barroso recording] None of the countries, or those 
where public opinion is, shall we say, more shocked by this 
situation, has so far advocated sending soldiers to the area to 
fight. One thing is troops to fight, another is blue helmets. 
The Blue Helmets -- many of them are almost hostages. They are 
witnessing massacres. Well, I ask myself whether it is very 
useful to have people witnessing massacres. Therefore, if we do 
not accept the possibility of massive military intervention, 
then we have to seek a political solution. [end recording] 
  Durao Barroso was speaking after a meeting with the Slovene 
foreign minister at Necessidades Palace [Foreign Ministry]. 
Durao Barroso also said that the success of the elections in 
South Africa could be a good start for the pacification of 
southern Africa. 
  [Begin Barroso recording] Contrary to a number of reports 
that have been made public which say the Portuguese Government's 
position is that the key to the issue lies in South Africa, I 
can say this is not true. There is a certain influence, but it 
would be an illusion to think that the Angolan problem will be 
resolved exclusively in South Africa, without denying, 
obviously, the links between the two situations. Of course, if 
the situation in South Africa evolves positively, with 
stability, with democracy, this can only be a positive factor 
for stability in the region, namely in Angola and Mozambique. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

