<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Notes EU Accession Progress </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Notes EU Accession Progress </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2004055794 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1600 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2004055794 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In an arrival statement at Larnaca Airport this 
afternoon, Foreign Minister Alekos Mikhailidhis said Cyprus has 
achieved very advanced positions at the European Union 
[EU]-Cyprus Association Council, which conferred in Luxembourg 
last night. Mikhailidhis described the Council's meeting as a 
great political achievement for Cyprus, because one of the two 
goals--to include Cyprus in the countries that will participate 
in the EU expansion--was achieved. The second goal, he said, 
was establishing a date to begin accession negotiations. 
  Referring to the joint statement of the Twelve, Mikhailidhis 
said the positions adopted are much more advanced than the ones 
we have had so far. He added that there is clear reference that 
human rights for all citizens must be safeguarded without any 
limitations or distinctions, and that any settlement or solution 
must be in line with the EU foundation principles. Mikhailidhis 
said: This means that the Cypriot Government's initial 
position--that a Cyprus solution must conform to EU principles 
and will allow us to enter and operate within the 
community--today has become an EU decision. 
  Discussing the confidence-building measures, the foreign 
minister said the joint statement clearly holds the Turkish side 
exclusively responsible and hails the Cypriot Government's 
constructive stance. 
  On the prospects of the EU accession of Cyprus, Mikhailidhis 
said January 1995 has already been set as the date to reevaluate 
Cyprus' application and the entire course for accession. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

