<F P=100> BENELUX COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> The Netherlands </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lubbers Advocates Strong Action Against Serbs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lubbers Advocates Strong Action Against Serbs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2204112894 Rotterdam ALGEMEEN DAGBLAD in Dutch 22 Apr 94 p 
3 </F>

<F P=103> BR2204112894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rotterdam ALGEMEEN DAGBLAD </F>
<F P=105>  Dutch </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Lubbers Calls For Strong Action </F>
Against Serbs"] 
  [Text] The Hague -- Prime Minister Lubbers feels that the 
international community must show that it is determined to end 
the war in Bosnia. He said this yesterday upon his departure 
from the Bulgarian capital of Sofia. 
  Foreign Minister Kooijmans, who accompanied Lubbers, noted 
that the chances for calling a halt to the war have dropped in 
the last two weeks. He also talked of a "common front," which 
must make it clear that the flagrant violations of the UN 
resolutions will no longer be tolerated. 
  The Netherlands had raised some questions about the request 
to NATO made by the UN secretary general to carry out air 
strikes around the "safe areas" in Bosnia. In a letter to the 
Second Chamber, Kooijmans said that "there must be better 
coordination with other countries that are supplying troops. 
There must also be a sufficient number of troops present in the 
"safe areas." 

</TEXT>

